title: For Sale/Trade:  Khyber Pass flintlock
postcontent: Here is something you don’t see every day... a cool and rare example of a Khyber Pass copy of a model 1805 Harper’s Ferry flintlock pistol. You can google it for more information, but Khyber Pass copies are firearms produced by the gunsmiths of the Khyber Pass between Pakistan and Afghanistan, known for hand crafting everything from crude to elaborate knock-offs of just about any firearm they could get their hands on for the last 200+ years. This pistol, unlike the original, does not have the 1805 Harper’s Ferry marking on the lock, nor any proofs or markings with the exception of the US eagle marking on the lock. The unrifled smooth-bore is .562 in diameter  (56 cal) as opposed to the .54 cal original and .58 cal Italian reproductions. These things are super scarce here in the states but not uncommon to find in the street markets of the Middle East. Most, if not all in the US were brought back by soldiers stationed overseas or by tourists.This is a super neat, functional black powder muzzle-loading flintlock with awesome patina. I have another Khyber Pass flintlock that dates to the Anglo-Afghan Wars, but I would say that this one is no older than the 1950s.Based on current winning auction bids on similar Khyber Pass copies, I’m asking $550

title: For Sale:  Brand new in box CZ-75 ‘Cold War’ Edition 9mm
postcontent: Selling Brand new in box CZ-75 ‘Cold War’ Edition chmbered in 9mmTo put it in the spirit of the Cold War, CZ cosmetically modified the basic design of the CZ-75B for this pistol. The most noticeable changes are the bright red stars on the slide and the Soviet hammer and sickle on the frame. These engravings are filled with a red lacquer and the roll marks on the slide are in Russian. These special rollmarks and engravings are a subtle, but a distinctive change to the standard CZ-75B. The bright red lacquer contrasts nicely with the typical CZ black polycoat finish.The pistol also borrows elements from the older “Pre-B” CZ-75. The squared off trigger guard is gone, replaced by a much more aesthetically pleasing rounded trigger guard. The ring hammer has also been replaced with a spur-type hammer. Even the controls resemble their counterparts on the Pre-B models.With the rounded trigger guard, the CZ-75B goes from a strictly utilitarian appearance to one of the nicer looking combat handguns. The Pre-B was also the most numerous variant produced during the Cold War, and is representative of the CZ-75 family during that era. I have installed half checkered wood colored deep-red to match the engraving.Included Original Box, Papers, Lock, One 10 round magazine, Cleaning Rod & Brush (Everything from Factory) Extras: Stainless Steel Guide Rod, 11 Lbs Recoil Spring, Red Wood CZ Grips (Original Parts Included)This is UNICORN, only 1000 guns has been made by CZ.
